[1] Wales vaccination plans
Date: Sat 31 May 2008
Source: The Veterinary Record 162:702, News & Reports [Subscription; edited]
<http://veterinaryrecord.bvapublications.com/cgi/content/full/162/22/702>


Wales prepares to declare a bluetongue protection zone
------------------------------------------------------
Vaccination against bluetongue is expected to begin in Wales on 2 Jun
2008, when the Welsh Assembly Government intends to declare a
protection zone in the south east of the country.

The announcement on 23 May 2008 by the Welsh rural affairs minister,
Ms. Elin Jones, followed an announcement the same day from DEFRA that
it planned 2 further extensions to the protection zone in England.
The 1st of these, which took place on 26 May 2008, extended the zone
to cover all of Devon. The 2nd extension is planned for 2 Jun 2008,
subject to the disease situation at that time, when DEFRA intends to
extend the zone to cover Cornwall, the East Riding of Yorkshire, West
Yorkshire, South Yorkshire, the district of Selby in North Yorkshire,
Warwickshire and Gloucestershire.

This latter extension will bring the English protection zone up to
the Welsh border, and will allow the Welsh Assembly Government to
declare the current restricted zone in south-east Wales a protection
zone. Under European law, vaccination against bluetongue can take
place only in a protection zone, and a protection zone can be
designated only if bluetongue is found to be circulating in an area
or if an area borders another protection zone. There are currently no
plans to change the zoning of the rest of Wales. However, the
Assembly Government says that further announcements on the roll-out
of the vaccination programme in Wales will be made subject to
veterinary advice and vaccine availability.

Ms. Jones said: "From Monday, 2 Jun 2008, subject to the delivery of
the vaccine from Intervet and other factors, we expect vaccination
against bluetongue will be able to begin in the current restricted
zone in south-east Wales. Over the past weeks, both the Assembly
Government and industry representatives have urged livestock keepers
to contact their vets and register their interest in the vaccine. If
farmers have not already done so, I would encourage them to do it now.

"The vaccine is the best defence we have against this disease. We
must take full advantage of it and I would urge those in the zone to
vaccinate their livestock."

One million doses of the vaccine against serotype 8 of the bluetongue
virus are expected to be available in the Welsh protection zone to
begin with. Wales has secured 2.5 million doses of the vaccine as
part of DEFRA's initial order of 22.5 million doses, and it is
jointly tendering with DEFRA for 5 million more doses for use in
Wales.

In a further announcement on 23 May 2008, the Welsh Assembly
Government said that, once a bluetongue protection zone had been
declared in Wales, animals from that zone would be able to travel to
the free zone of Wales direct to slaughter. The decision had been
made following a veterinary risk assessment, and the movement to
slaughter would be subject to specific controls through general
licensing. The risk assessment considered that areas that are now
being designated as part of the protection zone came as a result of
extensions of the zones to allow vaccination against the disease, not
as a result of increasing prevalence of the disease. There was no
evidence of a resurgence of the disease in these areas, and
vaccination within them would reduce the number of animals likely to
be infected.

