ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The concerns of the Welsh authorities which have led them to declare
now South East Wales as a Protection Zone, allowing preventive
vaccination against the threatening BTV-8, are supported by the fact
that the culicoides vector season is about to commence. As
illuminated by the French notification of 2 May 2008 (item [3]
above), the vector season seems to have already started in the
continent. Wales maintains a large, dense, highly susceptible sheep
population. The density of sheep in Wales exceeds 240 per sq/km --
significantly higher than the density prevailing in the BTV-8
affected area in South-Eastern England. Out of the total of about 34
million sheep in the UK, more than 9 million are located in Wales.
There is also a considerable, though much smaller, cattle population
in Wales; cattle, as we know, are also susceptible to BTV-8.

The following 2006 figures are derived from Farming Facts and
Figures, published in 2007 by the Welsh Assembly Government.
<http://new.wales.gov.uk/docrepos/40382/40382313/statistics/agriculture/agric-2007/farming-facts07-e2.pdf?lang=en>
a. Cattle
Dairy sector
Dairy cows: 281 000
Number of holdings with dairy cows: 3368
Average size of herd: 83
Beef sector
Beef cows: 223 600
Number of holdings with beef cows: 8478
Average size of herd: 26

b. Sheep sector
Total sheep and lambs: 9 350 700
Number of holdings: 15 271
Average size of flock: 612
Total breeding flock: 4 700 800
All other sheep 1 year old and over: 257 100
Lambs under 1 year: 4 392 800

Since the sheep grazing system in Wales includes a typical element of
seasonal translocation, when flocks move during the summer months to
pastures on higher altitudes where they are less accessible for
treatments, it seems desirable to vaccinate them before the movement.
- Mod.AS]
